Garlic bread ✨

No brainer recipe:

✨ Palak dal ✨

Comforting & nutritious 

Onions, chopped
3 Green Chillies, chopped
1 inch Ginger, chopped
2 tbsp Ghee
1 Tomato, chopped
1 tbsp Cumin seeds
1/2 tsp Asafoetida
1 tsp Red Chilli powder
1/2 tsp Turmeric powder
1 tbsp Coriander seed powder
1 cup Lentil/Toor Dal, boiled
Salt
2 cups Spinach leaves, chopped
Method of preparation:
Heat a pan, add ghee and allow it to heat.
Add cumin seeds, asafetida, onion, chilli, ginger, saute
it on high flame till the onions turn translucent.
Add red chilli powder, turmeric powder, coriander
powder, dal, tomatoes, salt and give it a good mix. Add spinach, mix well an let it cook.
Our Palak Dal is ready to serve.

Updating the recipe in awhile

I got a lot of responses to my avocado story and how I got it for 80rs. I was myself shocked as well. This is the Indian avocado. I have heard of it before but I’ve never found it online. I got this from Amazon while I was searching for avocado. I’ll put the link to this in my story. 

Link > https://amzn.to/3xlXTfa

Indian Avocados, or Butterfruits, are medium sized fruit with smooth, leathery, and glossy skin. These avocados have large seed pits and a creamy flesh that is lower in oil content in comparison with other avocado varieties. Avocados have existed in India only since the early 1900s, when they came to the country’s west coast by way of Sri Lanka. 

Also flavor wise, the Hass avocado tastes better as it has a higher fat percentage but in India it also retails for anywhere around 350rs per piece which is extremely expensive. It’s imported so naturally costs are higher.

Anyway, keto or not, avocados are highly nutritious and a good source of potassium and healthy fats!

The best indicator of ripeness is the color of the flesh itself. Before tossing out any avocado based on its exterior, cut it open: the pulp of a ripe butterfruit should be creamy and pale green.

✨Turkish Milk Cake✨

Ingredients: 

- 3 eggs
- 3/4 cup sugar 
- 1 tsp vanilla extract 
- 1 cup all purpose flour 
- 1 1/2 tsp baking powder 
- 1/2 cup milk 
- 1/4 cup oil 
- 1/4 tsp salt

Milk syrup: 

- 1 1/4 cup milk
- 1/4 cup condensed milk 
- 1 tsp vanilla extract 

Whip topping: 

- 3/4 cup non-dairy whipping cream
- 100g condensed milk
- 1 tsp vanilla extract 

Caramel sauce: (optional) 

- 1/2 cup castor sugar 
- 1/4 cup water 
- 1/4 cup fresh cream
- 2 tbsp butter 
- pinch of salt

Bake the cake at 180C for 45 minutes. Let it cool down completely then soak with the milk mix, add the whip topping on top & refrigerate overnight. Finally add the caramel sauce layer and serve!

Serving my favorite mac & cheese in this stunning @lamuse.in crockery – because presentation matters just as much as taste ✨

Ingredients:
	•	1 cup elbow macaroni (or any pasta you like)
	•	1 tbsp butter
	•	1 tbsp all-purpose flour
	•	1 cup milk (preferably warm, full-fat)
	•	1 cup grated cheese (cheddar is classic, or mix cheddar + mozzarella)
	•	Salt to taste
	•	Pepper or chili powder (optional)
	•	A pinch of nutmeg powder

Instructions:
	1.	Boil pasta:
Cook pasta in salted boiling water according to package instructions. Drain and set aside.
	2.	Make the roux (base for sauce):
In a pan, melt butter over medium heat. Add flour and whisk continuously for about 1 minute to cook the raw taste out.
	3.	Add milk:
Slowly pour in warm milk, whisking to avoid lumps. Cook for 2–3 minutes until it thickens slightly.
	4.	Add cheese:
Turn off the heat and stir in grated cheese until melted and smooth. Add salt and pepper & spices. 
	5.	Combine:
Add the cooked pasta to the cheese sauce and mix well until everything is coated. Transfer this into a baking dish cover with cheese and bake till the cheese on top has melted and developed a crust.
	6.	Serve:
Pour into a bowl or plate – preferably your beautiful La Muse crockery – and enjoy warm!

#littlehealthyish #macandcheeserecipe

Some tips: 

- make sure you are soaking your rice paper for 10 seconds
- make sure you are lining your steamer plate with a parchment paper
- don’t forget to also grease your parchment paper
- place the dumplings and keep a little space so that they don’t stick to each other

Apart from steaming, you can also fry them, however steaming tastes the best in my opinion 

For the filling I’ve used 
- minced chicken 
- salt, black pepper & white pepper 
- ginger garlic paste
- spring onion greens
- chili oil
- soy sauce 
- sesame oil

You can get creative and use prawns too or paneer and veggies for a vegetarian option. If you are using paneer and vegetables, maybe you can also try cooking the filling before wrapping up and steaming for more flavor 

#littlehealthyish #ricepaperdumplings #lowcaloriedumplings

Jokes aside, recipe: 

✨ No oven fudgy brownie ✨

You can, of course, make this in an oven as well.

Recipe:

- 2 eggs (or 1/2 cup hung curd)
- 1 cup sugar [200g]
- 1/2 cup oil or butter [120ml]
- 1/2 cup flour [60g]
- 6 tbsp cocoa powder [36g]
- Few drops of vanilla
- 100g melted chocolate [1/2 cup]
- Pinch of salt 

Always preheat the kadhai. Check after 30 mins. The middle of the brownie should still be wet/fudgy, the sides should be firm, that’s when you know it’s done. Do not overbake the brownie. Enjoy :) 

#littlehealthyish #noovenbaking #brownies #fudgybrownies #brownielovers 515492

✨ Garlic chili oil ✨

- neutral oil
- 20-25 cloves of garlic 
- 1 onion 
- 1/2 inch grated ginger
- 1 bay leaf 
- chili flakes
- red chili powder (adjust according to your taste)
- 2 tablespoon stock powder /bullion *
- 1 tablespoon soy sauce 

Tip: while I was frying my onion and garlic I also decided to add some dried red chilies. Cut them small with a scissor and add it in the end. Just let them get crispy, so fry for about 3 to 4 minutes, and I swear it is such an amazing texture to the chili oil!! 

* stock powder is my secret ingredient to add lots of umami to the chili oil. I have used chicken stock powder, but you can also use vegetarian stock cubes. They’re available on Amazon ✨

#littlehealthyish #chilioil 502705

✨iced tea✨

Recipe: 

- 2 tsp sugar 
- 2-3 tbsp tea leaves 
- 500ml water
- a pinch of salt
- squeeze of lime
- mint leaves, optional 

The reason why you don’t brew the tea for longer is because then it gets bitter and astringent. Especially for iced tea, the bitterness becomes even more noticeable because there is no heat to soften it 

#littlehealthyish #icedtearecipe #icedtea #lemonicetea
